Start();
search reset Grokking list;
register(Delim);

define
    DelimText isRule '('- dtext^}=delimiter;
    doc buffer;
    ;
print ``"M1: defined DelimText + doc":;

DatA += DelimText;
guard(DatA);
print ``"M2: grafted + guarded":;

debug StatemenT DelimText;
define
    doc = (/*****************************************************************************
                Live grammar mutation and delimiter capture

    A grammar rule in incant is a field. A field is a first-class object.
    That identity — rule equals field — is what makes this file possible.

    DelimText is a one-line rule that captures text opened by '(' and
    terminated by (and consuming) the closing delimiter. It can swallow anything
    inside that envelope: quotes, comments, newlines, arbitrary character
    sequences. It does not exist in incant until we add it here. The
    delimiter field referenced is an incant field defined at start up.

    What this file does is graft DelimText into DatA — one of incant's
    32 hard-coded bootstrap rules — at runtime, while incant is parsing
    with that very grammar. The graft requires exactly three lines, one
    rule, one expression, and a command:

        DelimText isRule '('- dtext}=delimiter;
        DatA += DelimText;      append the new alternative to the live rule
        guard(DatA);            clear the cached guard set so the parser
                                re-derives it, now seeing DelimText's opener

    On the very next definition, incant parses this entire comment through
    the alternative that did not exist when the session began. The proof is
    not a toy string. It is the text you are reading right now.

    This is not a reload. There is no recompile, no restart, no grammar
    file rewrite. The parser's own rule table is a live data structure,
    reachable and writable from incant code. Two operators, and the grammar
    mutates. The locomotive changes while the train stays on schedule.

    stop() exits incant and leaves the original bootstrap grammar in place
    and intact. The graft never persisted.

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Why guard() is not optional

    DatA's guard set — the set of characters that tell the parser which
    alternatives are worth trying — was computed at bootstrap and cached.
    A raw += graft grows the member list but leaves that cache untouched.
    The parser never sees DelimText's '(' opener, because it was never
    told to look for one. guard(DatA), called as a command, clears the
    cache and resets the derived flag, so the next parse re-derives the
    guard from scratch — now including the new opener.

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    POP — expected output

    DatA before the graft has five parse rule alternatives: GrouP, NumbeR,
    CodE, SetBrackets, NotA. After the graft, six — DelimText at the tail.
    The field doc comes back carrying this comment, parsed through the
    DelimText alternative that was not there when incant started.

    The definitions that make the demonstration run.

    delimiter    is not defined here; it is found by incant in the search list
                 generated by the search command defined in the incant grammar.
    DelimText    the rule grafted into DatA below. '(' opens it; } captures
                 into dtext up to and consuming delimiter. It is a rule without
                 a rule action; no need for one, the parser does all the work.
    doc          defined first as a buffer, then redefined here to capture this
                 comment by parsing it through the new DelimText alternative.
                 The buffer holds the captured text for use by subsequent
                 incant commands.
*****************************************************************************/
#);
    ;
print ``"M3: doc captured":;

printTO(doc);
print doc.dtext:;
print ``"--- WRITE 2 placeholder ---":;
printTO(null);

dumpContents(doc);
doc modedOP "/Users/anthony/Library/CloudStorage/Dropbox/data/InProcess/Groups/incant/grammarOnTheFly.out";
closeFile(doc);

stop();
